Porphyrion says he was the only one of his time who could write tragedy well. But the author of the ‘ Dialog. de Oratoribus’ asserts that both as a tragic writer and an orator his style was hard and dry. His history appears to have been in seventeen books 3 and it is after having heard him read a part of it (he is said to have introduced at Rome the custom of such readings to assemblieS, more or less familiar, before publication) that we may suppose Horace to have written the ode, of which the date is uncertain. Pollio appears to have been one of the most truly illustrious‚ and certainly one of the most accomplished‚ personages of the Augustan era.
